[4]
Date: Sat, 30 Aug 1997 13:03:54 -0400
From: Drzero@aol.com
I heard a brief mention on KABC radio, of a case, or possibly 2, of CJD in
people who had eaten squirrel brains. Usually KABC gets their items from a
published article [In this instance it was either the New York Times or The
Lancet]. It might be another item from one of those weekly papers you see in
the supermarket checkout lines.
I was on a backpacking survival trip in the high sierra a few weeks ago. We
caught several marmots [probably the yellowbelly marmot, _Marmota
flaviventris_] (similar to eastern woodchucks [_Marmonta monax_]) and ate
them. One participant who grew up on wild caught game ate the brains (which
weren't as well cooked as the rest of the meat). He said this was considered
a delicacy and they ate them all the time when he was a child.
---
Peter Cyrog, DVM
Los Angeles, Calif., USA
e-mail: Zero@aol.com>
[Keep in mind that no squirrels have been tested for "mad squirrel disease".
Although I wouldn't doubt for a minute that there is at least one squirrel
(genus _Sciurus_) retrovirus, as far as I know, none has been reported. This
sequence redefines the term "squirrely" but it is intriguing. -- Mod CHC]
